1 Introduction into tidyverse

From the official website tidyverse.org:

“The tidyverse is an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures.”

The most useful thing when learning the tidyverse is looking into their cheat sheets that include all important information about the specific package. For example, this is a cheat sheet for a dplyr package.

Remember, you always have to load library if you want to use some functions from there.

1.1 Install the complete tidyverse

install.packages("tidyverse")

You can see what is installed using the command:

library(tidyverse)

You can update all packages using the function tidyverse_update().

1.2 A tibble

Remember how we created the data frames using data.frame() function? In tidyverse, the data frames are called tibbles. They are much like the regular data frames, except printing and subsetting:

Tibbles have a refined print method that shows only the first 10 rows, and all the columns that fit on screen. This makes it much easier to work with large data. In addition to its name, each column reports its type, a nice feature borrowed from str():

library(tibble)

tibble(
  id = seq(1:5),
  rock_name = c("charnockite", "pyroxenite", "dunite", "volynite", "anorthosite"),
  is.altered = c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE)
)
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
##      id rock_name   is.altered
##   <int> <chr>       <lgl>     
## 1     1 charnockite TRUE      
## 2     2 pyroxenite  FALSE     
## 3     3 dunite      FALSE     
## 4     4 volynite    FALSE     
## 5     5 anorthosite FALSE

You can convert a data frame into tibble by using function as_tibble()

library(tibble)

df = data.frame(
  id = seq(1:5),
  rock_name = c("charnockite", "pyroxenite", "dunite", "volynite", "anorthosite"),
  is.altered = c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE)
)

as_tibble(df)
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
##      id rock_name   is.altered
##   <int> <fct>       <lgl>     
## 1     1 charnockite TRUE      
## 2     2 pyroxenite  FALSE     
## 3     3 dunite      FALSE     
## 4     4 volynite    FALSE     
## 5     5 anorthosite FALSE

3 Tidy data with tidyr

The package called tidyr is used to create tidy data representation.

The problem is that the same data may be represented in multiple ways using the table representation. Here are some examples with same data but different representations:

library(tidyr)

tibble(
  id = paste0(seq(1:5), '.sample'),
  mineral = c('magnetite', 'ilmenite', 'ilmenite', 'Cr-spinel', 'hercynite'),
  city = c('Banska Bystrica', 'Bratislava', 'Banska Bystrica', 'Banska Bystrica', 'Banska Bystrica'),
  institution = c('SAV', 'Geological Institute', 'SAV', 'SAV', 'SAV'),
  n_analyses = c(30, 119, 40, 20, 10)
)
## # A tibble: 5 x 5
##   id       mineral   city            institution          n_analyses
##   <chr>    <chr>     <chr>           <chr>                     <dbl>
## 1 1.sample magnetite Banska Bystrica SAV                          30
## 2 2.sample ilmenite  Bratislava      Geological Institute        119
## 3 3.sample ilmenite  Banska Bystrica SAV                          40
## 4 4.sample Cr-spinel Banska Bystrica SAV                          20
## 5 5.sample hercynite Banska Bystrica SAV                          10
tibble(
  id = paste0(seq(1:5), '.sample'),
  mineral = c('magnetite', 'ilmenite', 'ilmenite', 'Cr-spinel', 'hercynite'),
  lab = c('SAV, Banska Bystrica', 'Geological Institute, Bratislava', 'SAV, Banska Bystrica', 'SAV, Banska Bystrica', 'SAV, Banska Bystrica'),
  n_analyses = c(30, 119, 40, 20, 10)

In order to make things clear, we’ll use next terminology:

  1. A variable is a column.
  2. An observation is a row.
  3. A cell in the table is a value.

tidyr functions fall into five main categories. We will not dive into those, because they are a bit complicated.

3.1 Pivotting

Converts between long and wide forms. tidyr 1.0.0 introduces pivot_longer() and pivot_wider(). See vignette("pivot") for more details.

3.2 Rectangling

Turns deeply nested lists (as from JSON) into tidy tibbles. See unnest_longer(), unnest_wider(), hoist(), and vignette("rectangle") for more details.

3.3 Nesting

Converts grouped data to a form where each group becomes a single row containing a nested data frame, and unnesting does the opposite. See nest(), unnest(), and vignette("nest") for more details.

3.4 Splitting and combining character columns

Use separate() and extract() to pull a single character column into multiple columns; use unite() to combine multiple columns into a single character column.

As you may see, this data is a bit wide.. We might want to convert it to a longer format, eg have the oxides as variables (columns) and analyses as observations (rows) - that is more logical in our case. The latter could be done with regular function t() which transposes objects:

initial_data_t <- t(initial_data)
colnames(initial_data_t) <- initial_data_t[1,]
initial_data_t <- as_tibble(cbind(Sample = names(initial_data)[-1], initial_data_t[-1,]))

initial_data_t <- 
  initial_data_t %>%
  mutate_at(vars(-Sample, -Origin, -Reference), as.numeric) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(-Sample, -Origin, -Reference), .funs=function(x){ replace(x, x<=0, NA) })

4 dplyr basics

Dplyr is a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of verbs that help you solve the most common data manipulation challenges.

Dplyr provides an alternative syntax for chaining or combining multiple functions, or calling a single function:

select(initial_data_t, SiO2)
## # A tibble: 143 x 1
##     SiO2
##    <dbl>
##  1  0.02
##  2  0.02
##  3  0.04
##  4  0.02
##  5  0.11
##  6 NA   
##  7 NA   
##  8 NA   
##  9 NA   
## 10 NA   
## # … with 133 more rows

which is the same as this

initial_data_t %>%
  select(SiO2)
## # A tibble: 143 x 1
##     SiO2
##    <dbl>
##  1  0.02
##  2  0.02
##  3  0.04
##  4  0.02
##  5  0.11
##  6 NA   
##  7 NA   
##  8 NA   
##  9 NA   
## 10 NA   
## # … with 133 more rows

%>% operator is called a pipe operator. Its syntax is very simple and it allows you to omit the data argument of tidyverse functions.

There are 5 most useful functions within this package.

4.1 Functions to work with observations (rows)

4.1.1 filter()

It allows you to choose rows based on column values.

Let’s filter our dataframe by those rows satisfying the criteria

initial_data_t %>%
  filter(Al2O3 > 50 & `BeO calc.` <= 19)

Note, the same could be written as:

filter(initial_data_t, Al2O3 > 50 & `BeO calc.` <= 19)

To use filtering effectively, you have to know how to select the observations that you want using the comparison operators. R provides the standard suite: >, >=, <, <=, != (not equal), and == (equal).

Multiple arguments to filter() are combined with “and”: every expression must be true in order for a row to be included in the output. For other types of combinations, you’ll need to use Boolean operators yourself: & is “and”, | is “or”, and ! is “not”. Additionally, there’s a useful short-hand for selecting values satisfying multiple criteria using x %in% y. This will select every row where x is one of the values in y.

initial_data_t %>% 
  filter(Origin %in% c('Magmatic leucogranite', 'Contaminated ultrabasic rock'))

4.2 Functions to work with variables (columns)

4.3 Functions to work with groups of observations (rows)

4.3.1 summarise()

It allows you to collapse a group into a single row using a specific function as an argument.

For, example, we can calculate few stats for the whole data frame:

initial_data_t %>% 
  summarise(silica_min = min(SiO2, na.rm=TRUE), min_alumina = min(Al2O3, na.rm=TRUE))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   silica_min min_alumina
##        <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1      0.004        13.4

However, that’s not very useful. Consider a task when we might want to calculate some stats based on the factors (or groups). For example, in our case we want to see what is the mean value of FeO, Cr2O3, TiO2 and BeO for each origin type. There’s where a group_by() comes in handy!

4.3.2 group_by()

group_by() takes an existing tbl and converts it into a grouped tbl where operations are performed “by group”. Let’s see an example.

What happens if we do this?

initial_data_t %>% 
  summarise(`BeO mean` = mean(`BeO calc.`))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `BeO mean`
##        <dbl>
## 1       18.4

…right. A mean value for all rows. But we want a mean BeO for each origin group! Let’s do this:

initial_data_t %>% 
  group_by(Origin) %>%
  summarise(`BeO mean` = mean(`BeO calc.`))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 8 x 2
##   Origin                          `BeO mean`
##   <chr>                                <dbl>
## 1 Actinolite schist                     19.2
## 2 Albite-petalite pegmatite (pod)       19.7
## 3 Contaminated pegmatite                19.1
## 4 Contaminated syenite pegmatite        19.7
## 5 Contaminated ultrabasic rock          16.0
## 6 Granulite facies metapelite           19.9
## 7 Magmatic leucogranite                 19.7
## 8 Metamorphosed pegmatite               19.6

We may calculate as many variables per group as we wish:

initial_data_t %>% 
  group_by(Origin) %>%
  summarise(`BeO mean` = mean(`BeO calc.`, na.rm=TRUE), 
            `FeO mean` = mean(FeO, na.rm=TRUE), 
            `Cr2O3 mean` = mean(Cr2O3, na.rm=TRUE), 
            `TiO2 mean` = mean(TiO2, na.rm=TRUE)
            )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 8 x 5
##   Origin                          `BeO mean` `FeO mean` `Cr2O3 mean` `TiO2 mean`
##   <chr>                                <dbl>      <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 Actinolite schist                     19.2      0.405       0.225        0.1  
## 2 Albite-petalite pegmatite (pod)       19.7      0.194       0.023        0.244
## 3 Contaminated pegmatite                19.1      0.13        0.68         0.15 
## 4 Contaminated syenite pegmatite        19.7      0.37      NaN            0.41 
## 5 Contaminated ultrabasic rock          16.0      0.200      54.2          0.594
## 6 Granulite facies metapelite           19.9    NaN           0.903      NaN    
## 7 Magmatic leucogranite                 19.7      0.338       0.0325       0.358
## 8 Metamorphosed pegmatite               19.6      0.129       0.09         0.167

As well as grouping by existing variables, like in the previous example, you can group by any function of existing variables. This is equivalent to performing a mutate() before the group_by():

initial_data_t %>% 
    mutate(Ti_group = if_else(TiO2 > 1, 'high', 'low')) %>%
    group_by(Ti_group) %>%
    summarise(`BeO mean` = mean(`BeO calc.`, na.rm=TRUE), 
              `FeO mean` = mean(FeO, na.rm=TRUE), 
              `Cr2O3 mean` = mean(Cr2O3, na.rm=TRUE), 
              `TiO2 mean` = mean(TiO2, na.rm=TRUE)
    )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   Ti_group `BeO mean` `FeO mean` `Cr2O3 mean` `TiO2 mean`
##   <chr>         <dbl>      <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 high           15.1      0.168         63.3       1.72 
## 2 low            18.2      0.206         38.8       0.301
## 3 <NA>           19.4      0.103         22.7     NaN

5 Data visualization with ggplot

Let’s finally dive into visualizing the data!

We will be using ggplot2 package, which is a part of tidyverse ecosystem.

It’s hard to succinctly describe how ggplot2 works because it embodies a deep philosophy of visualisation. However, in most cases you start with ggplot(), supply a dataset and aesthetic mapping (with aes()). You then add on layers (like geom_point() or geom_histogram()), scales (like scale_colour_brewer()), faceting specifications (like facet_wrap()) and coordinate systems (like coord_flip()).

See the examples of ggplot2 visualizations to know more.

Here’s a simple example with the previous dataset.

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data = initial_data_t) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = `BeO calc.`, y = TiO2))
## Warning: Removed 42 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Accordingly, a reusable template for making graphs with ggplot2 would be:

ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))

where

  • DATA is a tibble or a data frame,
  • GEOM_FUNCTION - how to visualize the data,
  • MAPPINGS - which variables to use and how

What happens when we run ggplot(data = initial_data_t)?

Open the cheat sheet to start exploring this library.

5.1 Scatter plot

Let’s start with a simple scatter binary plot. Try to plot TiO2 on X axis with Cr2O3 on Y axis for our dataframe!

ggplot(data = initial_data_t) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = TiO2, y = Cr2O3))
## Warning: Removed 86 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Let’s change the color of the points and adjust their size:

ggplot(data = initial_data_t) +
